# Write Tool Execution — Pending Action Protocol

Every Audric write (save, send, swap, borrow, repay, claim, harvest) goes through the same protocol. Get any step wrong and either (a) the user double-confirms, (b) the agent forgets the action happened, or (c) the wrong row's outcome is overwritten in `TurnMetrics`.

> **Post-S.245 + S.269 + S.277:** `pay_api`, `volo_stake`, `volo_unstake`, and `save_contact` were removed from the engine surface. Same protocol still applies to the remaining 8 write tools (`save_deposit`, `withdraw`, `borrow`, `repay_debt`, `send_transfer`, `claim_rewards`, `harvest_rewards`, `swap_execute`).

> **Post-v0.7c / v0.7e (the standalone `/api/engine/resume` route is GONE):** resume is folded inline into `/api/chat`. The client uses the AI SDK `useChat` HITL pattern — approving (or denying) a tool call auto-fires the **next** `/api/chat` turn carrying the resolved tool part; the route walks it via `extractResumeOutcomes()` (`lib/audric/resume-outcome.ts`) and runs the `updateMany` itself. There is no separate resume POST anymore. The chat surface is `app/chat/audric-chat-client.tsx` (not the old `app/page.tsx`), and confirm UI is `components/audric/permission-card.tsx` (not `components/engine/cards/`).

## The 6-step protocol

```
Step 1 — Engine yields pending_action
Step 2 — Audric persists attemptId on TurnMetrics (at chat-time, in /api/chat)
Step 3 — Audric renders PermissionCard with modifiableFields
Step 4 — User taps Confirm (with optional edits)
Step 5 — handleExecuteAction runs the sponsored tx flow + addToolResult
Step 6 — useChat auto-fires the next /api/chat turn carrying the resolved tool part
         → /api/chat calls extractResumeOutcomes() + updateMany({ where: { attemptId } })
         → engine consumes the tool result → next turn knows the tx happened
```

## Step 1 — `pending_action` shape (what the engine sends)

```typescript
{
  type: 'pending_action',
  action: {
    toolName: 'save_deposit',
    toolUseId: 'toolu_xxx',
    input: { asset: 'USDC', amount: 10 },
    description: 'Save 10 USDC at NAVI (3.2% APY)',
    assistantContent: [...],     // Full LLM message that triggered
    completedResults: [...],     // Auto-approved tool results in same turn
    guardInjections: [...],      // _hint / _warning from runGuards
    modifiableFields: [{ name: 'amount', kind: 'amount', asset: 'USDC' }],
    turnIndex: 4,                // Monotonic turn counter (legacy fallback key)
    attemptId: 'a1b2c3d4-...',   // UUID v4 — the only resume key for new code
  },
}
```

## Step 2 — Persist `attemptId` at chat-time

In `/api/chat/route.ts`, when the SSE stream emits `pending_action`:

```typescript
// chat/route.ts collector pattern
collector.onPendingAction(event.action.attemptId);

// At end of turn, write the TurnMetrics row WITH attemptId:
await prisma.turnMetrics.create({
  data: {
    sessionId,
    turnIndex,
    attemptId: collector.attemptId,        // ← REQUIRED
    // ... other metrics
  },
});
```

Skipping `attemptId` here means the resume route can't find the row → outcome telemetry is lost forever.

## Step 3 — Render the confirm card

```tsx
// apps/web-v2/app/chat/audric-chat-client.tsx → components/audric/permission-card.tsx
<PermissionCard
  action={pendingAction}
  modifiableFields={pendingAction.modifiableFields}
  onConfirm={(edits) => handleExecuteAction(pendingAction, edits)}
  onDecline={() => handleDeclineAction(pendingAction)}
/>
// Multi-step bundles render via <BundlePermissionCard>.
```

Confirm card MUST:
- Show the plain-English `description`.
- Surface every `_warning` from `guardInjections` prominently.
- Allow editing only the fields in `modifiableFields` (don't allow edits the engine didn't authorize).
- Call out gas sponsorship ("Free — Audric pays the gas").
- Have a clear Decline option that's visually equal to Confirm (no dark patterns).

## Step 4 — User taps Confirm

User edits are applied in `app/chat/audric-chat-client.tsx` (the modification logic is inline in the chat client — there is no separate `apply-modifications.ts`), producing a new `input` object the engine will see on resume. Only the fields the engine listed in `modifiableFields` may change.

## Step 5 — Execute via sponsored tx

`handleExecuteAction` in `apps/web-v2/app/chat/audric-chat-client.tsx`:

```typescript
async function handleExecuteAction(action, edits) {
  const finalInput = applyModifications(action, edits);

  const prep = await fetch('/api/transactions/prepare', {
    method: 'POST',
    body: JSON.stringify({ toolName: action.toolName, input: finalInput }),
  });
  const { sponsoredTxBytes, sponsoredSig } = await prep.json();

  const userSig = await signWithEphemeralKey(sponsoredTxBytes);

  const exec = await fetch('/api/transactions/execute', {
    method: 'POST',
    body: JSON.stringify({ sponsoredTxBytes, sponsoredSig, userSig }),
  });
  const { tx: txDigest, balanceChanges } = await exec.json();

  // Render receipt — parse balanceChanges client-side (NOT the SDK return shape)
  renderReceipt(action, txDigest, balanceChanges);

  // Step 6 — hand the result back to useChat. This appends an
  // `output-available` tool part (carrying the client-measured
  // writeToolDurationMs) and auto-fires the next /api/chat turn.
  addToolResult({
    tool: action.toolName,
    toolCallId: action.toolUseId,
    output: { txDigest, balanceChanges, modifiedInput: finalInput },
  });
}
```

## Step 6 — Resume is handled inline in `/api/chat`

There is no `/api/engine/resume` route. When `useChat` auto-fires the next turn, the request body's LAST assistant message carries the resolved tool part (`state: 'output-available'` when confirmed, `state: 'output-error'` when denied / failed). `/api/chat/route.ts` walks it and persists the outcome:

```typescript
// apps/web-v2/app/api/chat/route.ts (extractResumeOutcomes ← lib/audric/resume-outcome.ts)
const resumeOutcomes = extractResumeOutcomes(body.messages);
for (const o of resumeOutcomes) {
  // persistResumeOutcome → updateMany keyed on attemptId (== AI SDK approvalId).
  await prisma.turnMetrics.updateMany({
    where: { attemptId: o.attemptId },
    data: {
      pendingActionOutcome: o.outcome,
      writeToolDurationMs: o.writeToolDurationMs,
    },
  });
}
```

Fire-and-forget — it never blocks the response stream. Idempotent: the same tool part rides every subsequent turn's history, so re-running `updateMany` overwrites with the same value (the route only walks the LAST assistant message to avoid re-updating older HITL rows). The engine then continues the conversation — its next turn's context includes the executed tool's result, so it narrates "Done. You're now earning 3.2% on $10 USDC."

## What happens if you skip `attemptId`

| Skip step | Symptom |
|---|---|
| Step 2 (persist) | Resume can't find TurnMetrics row → outcome telemetry lost |
| Step 6 (no `addToolResult`) | Engine doesn't know tx happened → next turn offers to retry → user rejects → confusion |
| Step 6 (wrong key) | Same `(sessionId, turnIndex)` pair matches multiple rows → wrong row gets overwritten → metrics regression |

## Modifiable fields — what the user can edit

Sourced from `tool-modifiable-fields.ts` in the engine. Adding a new editable field:

1. Add to the engine's `tool-modifiable-fields.ts` map.
2. The modification logic in `app/chat/audric-chat-client.tsx` handles `kind: 'amount'` and `kind: 'address'` — extend it for new kinds.
3. Add a UI control to `PermissionCard` for the new kind.

## What's banned

```typescript
// ❌ Auto-execute under zkLogin
permissionLevel: 'auto'  // for any write tool

// ❌ Forget attemptId on TurnMetrics
prisma.turnMetrics.create({ data: { sessionId, turnIndex /* no attemptId */ } });

// ❌ POST a dead resume route — it no longer exists; resume is inline in /api/chat
await fetch('/api/engine/resume', { body: JSON.stringify({ txDigest, attemptId }) });

// ❌ Trust the SDK return shape under sponsored flow
const result: SwapResult = await /* /api/transactions/execute */;
result.toAmount;  // doesn't exist — server only returns { tx, balanceChanges }

// ✅ Parse balanceChanges client-side
const change = balanceChanges?.find((c) => c.coinType === USDC_TYPE);
const usdcDelta = Number(change?.amount ?? 0) / 1e6;
```

